        "value": "\"@type\": \"Question\","
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"name\": \"How much does an M157 or M178 engine replacement cost?\",",
        "value": "\"acceptedAnswer\": {"
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"@type\": \"Answer\",",
        "value": "\"text\": \"A reconditioned M157/M178 typically costs £6,500–£10,000 supply only, with fitting adding £1,300–£2,000 depending on labour rates [ESTIMATED]. AMG-specific parts and specialist labour drive costs significantly above standard Mercedes engines.\""
      },
      {
        "metric": "}",
        "value": "},"
      },
      {
        "metric": "{",
        "value": "\"@type\": \"Question\","
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"name\": \"Is the M157/M178 a reliable engine?\",",
        "value": "\"acceptedAnswer\": {"
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"@type\": \"Answer\",",
        "value": "\"text\": \"The M157/M178 rates 3.5★ out of 5 — powerful and rewarding when maintained, but known for bore scoring, timing chain wear on early M157s, and oil leaks. Regular servicing by an AMG specialist is non-negotiable.\""
      },
      {
        "metric": "}",
        "value": "},"
      },
      {
        "metric": "{",
        "value": "\"@type\": \"Question\","
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"name\": \"What is the most common M157/M178 failure?\",",
        "value": "\"acceptedAnswer\": {"
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"@type\": \"Answer\",",
        "value": "\"text\": \"Cylinder bore scoring is the most catastrophic, particularly on poorly maintained or overheated examples. Early M157s also suffer timing chain stretch and oil wicking into wiring harnesses.\""
      },
      {
        "metric": "}",
        "value": "},"
      },
      {
        "metric": "{",
        "value": "\"@type\": \"Question\","
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"name\": \"Which Mercedes models use the M157/M178?\",",
        "value": "\"acceptedAnswer\": {"
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"@type\": \"Answer\",",
        "value": "\"text\": \"The M157 powers the S 63, CL 63, E 63, CLS 63, G 63, GL 63, ML 63 (2011–2015+). The M178 replaced it from 2014 onward, powering the AMG GT range, W213 E 63, and newer G 63 / GT 4-Door.\""
      },
      {
        "metric": "}",
        "value": "},"
      },
      {
        "metric": "{",
        "value": "\"@type\": \"Question\","
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"name\": \"How long does the M157/M178 last?\",",
        "value": "\"acceptedAnswer\": {"
      },
      {
        "metric": "\"@type\": \"Answer\",",
        "value": "\"text\": \"With meticulous maintenance, 100,000–150,000 miles is achievable. However, bore scoring can appear as early as 40,000–60,000 miles on neglected examples, and timing chain issues typically emerge around 60,000–100,000 miles.\""
      },
      {
        "metric": "}",
        "value": "}"
